When I was younger, I used to watch a multitude of YouTubers play the early versions of this game with just a single map. I couldn't wait for the early access to launch, even though I had no computer at the time. This game was one of the main reasons I wanted one, and it was DEFINITELY worth the wait when I finally got to play it.

This game is extremely fun, even without community content. The physics make some [i]really[/i] funny situations, and the sound effects and messy unit limbs make it even better. But the [i]real[/i] fun starts when you spam overpowered units in the sandbox, and let them run loose on hordes of peasants and halflings. And then the even REALER fun begins when you use bugs to make units with 15+ abilities and 10x attack speed that get into fights straight out of Dragonball!!!

I'm [b]SURE[/b] that this game will continue to thrive for years to come on the abundance of mods and custom content that people spend weeks working on to share with the rest of the community, even without any content updates from Landfall. It's funny, it's cool, and at the same time able to be really challenging if you play by the books.

TL;DR: This game was worth the wait, and can be very fun with or without community content.

This game is now better than ever, every update they add is really not just some more content, it's a very creative and gamechanging new way of playing the game. It's basically a sandbox where you can simulate a battle between any characters  you want and with the physics this game has it's a recipe for limitless fun, you can literally spend hours just seeing this goofy characters battle each other. You also have a big campaign where you can only spend a limited amount of money on your troops in order to defeat a predetermined set of enemies. You're normally just a floating camera that watches the battlefield but now you are also able to "possess" your characters and see a first person perspective of the battle while using that character's ability. They have also added god like powers to you so you can summon a tornado in the battlefield or start shooting arrows from the sky.
 As they don't stop adding new stuff there's also a way to create your own characters as well as campaigns, you can then share them at the steam workshop and enjoy another infinite time of fun.
 I would definitely recommend this game for a fun experience, bonus points if you got a friend home who you can laugh with for hours

This game is perfect. Like, it's genuinely perfect. It has various well-designed pre-made levels that are really fun, and seeing a bunch of goofy troops stumbling around trying to kill the enemy is hilarious, with the troops themselves being really creative and fun to tinker around with. However, where the game shines the most is its custom content creator. You can not only create, design and balance your own troops, levels and campaigns, but the editors for all of them are really versatile and don't require even the slightest bit of coding. This game is a must-play for any Steam user out there, especially for people who love extremely versatile custom content creation.

This game may not have everything from the earlier builds, but it's even better than it was before!

All the units have proper outfits that let them be told apart, it's still a funny game with the ragdoll physics, and the custom units can add to an already great game!

When it was in pre-alpha, open alpha, and closed alpha, some games here on Steam (*fake cough* Battle Beast Simulator and Ultimate Epic Battle Simulator *fake cough*) copied its basic idea even if they put their own twist on it. In the two examples I gave, one has animals from prehistory and the present, weapons you can give them, turrets, soccer, and breaking boxes, while the other allows for WAY bigger armies to fight. There are probably more clones of TABS out there.

If you haven't figured it out yet, the name "Totally Accurate Battle Simulator" is sarcasm.

PROS:
All the humanoid units are fully clothed, unlike the Pre-Alpha, Open Alpha, and Closed Alpha
The physics are hilarious and make it so even if all the units are placed in the exact same spots, the outcome of which units survive can be different even if the same team wins
They learned from the mistakes of making jokes about politics (since the Open Alpha and Closed Alpha had units to tie into the United States' 2016 presidential election, those being a Hillary Clinton unit who threw emails that served as more damaging ninja stars and a Donald Trump unit who dual wielded M16s and could summon a wall to both protect himself before the wall fell down on his foes)
They finally added stuff based on the Closed Alpha's Neon faction to the Unit Creator, though it's also the last major update to TABS
The Unit Creator lets you make your own units, though there are some things Landfall made that you can't replicate with the vanilla Unit Creator

CONS:
There aren't counterparts to every unit from the Pre-Alpha, Open Alpha, or Closed Alpha, though most of them do have counterparts

Overall, I'd recommend the full release of TABS.

I really love this game. I have played this game for over 900 hours altogether. The one thing I would suggest is adding a search bar when you're adding battles to custom campaigns. Because if you get filled up on that, it's impossible to find the right battles in the right order in which you do them in.

Fun game, but maybe a bit poorly balanced - you can use the same few units to win most fights, which makes it a bit too easy, while other fights are obnoxiously difficult and RNG-based. Still, it actually seems surprisingly "accurate" in many ways, e. g. how to utilize shields and pointy sticks, combining ranged units with melee units or the use of cavalry / fast units. 

If you want this game to stay entertaining in the long-run, you'll need to come up with ways to challenge yourself. Maybe joining the multiplayer mode is a good option too, haven't tried it (and probably won't, due to the aforementioned balance issues).

Either way, definitely worth it at a discount. Potentially worth it at the regular price if you're good at entertaining yourself or if even more campaigns are added.

Overall, this is what I have to say:
Pros:
+ Myriad different units to battle with.
+ The units themselves seem quirky and entertaining.
+ Combat mechanics are pretty decent, albeit choppy at times.
+ Audios and map concepts in-game are both pretty good.
+ Campaign mode available, to get more units, or leaderboards.
+ An overall good time killer, with a lot of funny quirks and features.
Cons:
- Can be VERY laggy at times.
- Unit AI sometimes breaks or lags behind a bit.
- Very costly money-wise.
Neutral:
= Unsure what the DLC actually contributes to the game.
Overall: 4/5

[b]Sights & Sounds[/b]
- The combatants and environments are both heavily stylized and goofy-looking. It's consistently amusing to see armies of low-poly, googly-eyed warriors clumsily wailing on each other
- The sounds only add to the chaos. With all the clanking swords, fiery explosions, and sparkling magic spells, there's always a noisy cacophony to greet you whenever you hit the Start button

[b]Story & Vibes[/b]
- It should come to no surprise that a game that plays more like a toy wouldn't have a story. Just pick your troops and get to bashing

[b]Playability & Replayability[/b]
- Although there's a "story" mode full of scenarios, they're all very simple to beat, and it won't take you long to do so
- You'll be given a set of armies to choose from and a limited number of points to spend. Sometimes you're restricted to certain armies or troops. As you may expect, higher point costs usually mean a stronger unit
- Where this game really shines, however, is as a dumb couch co-op game where you come up with arbitrary rules, have your armies duke it out, and enjoy all the physics sandbox chaos
- It's replayable, but it will get old pretty quick. TABS is, if nothing else, a one-trick pony

[b]Overall Impressions & Performance[/b]
- I much preferred playing this game on the couch with either my wife or some friends. However, I don't think I've ever played a session if this game that lasted longer than 90 minutes. You get bored and move on pretty quick
- The game mostly runs fine, but it won't be long before you have so many things being simulated on the screen that slowdown and framiness are virtually inevitable. It's part of the fun

[b]Final Verdict[/b]
- [b]5.5/10[/b]. It's some mild fun with friends, but don't expect it much out of it beyond that

Game will forever be special to me as I've known of this game since it was in its open alpha phase when Donald Trump and Hillary Clinton were still in the game, which was back in elementary school when I was in 5th grade and as of now I am currently a Senior in High School (I feel old when I think back). 

Personal reasons aside now. Tabs (short form for Totally Accurate Battle Simulator) is a sandbox battle esc game where you have PLENTY of things you can do. Ranging from doing the basic things such as the several totally accurate battles in the campaigns (see what I did there?) or playing against a buddy in a multiplayer match to see who can beat the others units and leave the other crying in a corner over their loss. OR you can dig further and try to find the secret units hidden around the maps in sandbox mode, create your own custom units to use or upload to the community. OR DIG EVEN FURTHER! and experiment with some mods, go crazy with said mods and break the game more than you can already break it in the vanilla game! OR......... go EVEN FURTHER BEYOND and create some custom campaigns, make your own story, make some lore for your campaign/story, get creative (or don't and be basic). ORRRRRR GO EVEN DEEPER THAN BEFORE! and even create YOUR OWN MAPS! mix it all together and well........... You can have a game that has one limit, that being yourself.

Basically to sum this delightful game up tabs (Totally Accurate Battle Simulator) is a game that really has ABSOLUTELY no limits, you make the fun, YOU are the fun (if you do all of what I said). 

FULLY SUMMED UP..................... Totally Accurate Battle Simulator is a 9/10 game if you can play it with a creative mindset and a 6.5/10 if you play everything without experimentation.

Totally accurate. They portrayed the sacred elephant time of history perfectly. I honestly can't believe how much fact-checking went into this. And don't get me started on that crazy lore! You thought the FNaF lore was convoluted, you haven't seen nothing yet. But the ending, is just fantastic once you realize the true lore. I love that where Lord Wonkey Eye said "It's wonkin' time". Truly one of the best moments in cinema history. If there ever was a TABS movie to cover the lore it would be longer than your whole lifetime. Even MatPat cannot fathom the lore. The gameplay is so accurate to real life events that it's shocking how good it is. I love the part in Chapter 9 where the name contradicts what happens, as you do not get killed. The audacity there is profound. Not even peak Valve could come up with twists and turns this much times. It's like Half Life 2 but now for battle simulators. The graphics are so realistic, don't let the previews fool you. The secrets too are just top notch, like how they have a Pit Boss achievement for falling into a pit in level 3. I honestly think TABS 2 could never live up to this. The audio though is top notch, it's better than every OST on the planet. The plot twist at the end is so good it stuns me every playthrough. Totally Accurate Battle Simulator is about as accurate as it gets. It's goofy, fun, and balanced (except a few units but there's gotta be a few busted characters). I love the ability to posses a character, it's very fun to mess around as different units like the sharp shooter or even just wobble around as a halfling. The campaigns are also fun little challenges to beat. There are also plenty of secret characters, maps, and even extra campaigns to unlock by finding secrets in the different maps. Overall, it's a very fun and wacky tactical war sim. I just wish that they kept the Chicken Man and the Chicken Man Man in the final game...

Simple, funny, creative, engaging gameplay. The main loop is that you are confronted with a specific enemy army and need to place your units with the currency limit of that level before the battle commences. By pressing F while aiming at a unit you can control it. It is addictive and hilarious. Not a co op game but we ended up playing together with my SO at home by just deciding which units to use and where to place them. The sole strategy planning is great and can make for a great time of laughs. No blood nor gore (which is nice IMO) but just ridiculous encounters. Straight into my favourites' list.

I am 27.

My ex-wife and I have a daughter together, and adopted our son together. They are now both 4 years old.

When we were going through our separation, I found myself lost and miserable. I was self destructive. I got so mad one day from everything spiraling out of my control that I punched some concrete in a moment of overwhelming emotion. That caused me to break my 5th metacarpal in my right hand... my working hand... my games hand.. the hand that I held and carried my children to bed with.. The hand I desperately needed to make sure I could continue to provide.

After learning of the severity of my self-inflicted damage, I was borderline suicidal. Keep in mind that just a few months before this, I was the happiest man with no history of depression or anxiety. I have never had fits of rage, or been one to break down and cry, but I was in a low spot that just really buried me from being able to see the light on the other side.

Having nothing better to do, I searched for a game I could play, ONE HANDED while I recovered. I somehow stumbled upon this game and read some of the reviews. I decided that it had to be worth a shot... I must admit, I didn't beat the game, or play nearly as long as some of you. In fact, I may have only played this game a day or two.. With that being said, after doing so, I had a new found joy and hope for life. I was able to put behind me the pain and suffering that had been cast over me. I was able to experience other peoples joy and happiness. I was able to see the fruits of my "labor". I relaxed for 5 fucking minutes to this music long enough to realize that I was going to be okay.

After coming to that realization, I turned the game off, and I went back to work. It hurt my hand like hell but I was motivated. I stopped feeling so damn sorry for myself, and I became the father I needed to be in that moment, not the weak boy I was behaving as.

Today, I am close friend with my kids mother. We don't fight, or argue, or say hurtful things to each other. We are parents, and friends.

I now have 3 kids. My third child is, wait for it, ALSO 4 YEARS OLD. The woman I am with was going through a very similar situation at the time of my own separation, and we just stumbled in to each others life unexpectedly. We have been in a relationship for a year now, and are very happy together.

Moral of the story, you never know what life holds in store for you, and if I would have given up when all the odds were stacked against me, I wouldn't be where I am today. This silly little game helped me realize that.

ever want to have an army of cavemen vs a M1 Abram? well here you can have that! and more! simulate any battles with both game-made characters and custom community made characters. hell, you can even create your own characters and on top of that, you can download mods that have so many useful things in them, it will make the in-game unit creator look like a cake walk.
you might be wondering. "what about the maps?" well I am glad that you most likely did not ask! there are large number of game given maps and simulation that you can use as the terrain for your battle, as well as interact with by finding hidden items for secret units. on top of that, in one of their more recent updates, they added the map creator, which allows for hundreds of thousands of map possibilities, its pretty neat.
the downsides of course are that this game runs purely off of physics. for those of you who are ignorant of what I mean, most games that simulate a battle generally use pre-made animations for when someone dies, or swings, or runs, or anything really.  this game however uses a physics engine that essentially makes the "gumbies" move without custom animation, as well as literally anything you can imagine. optimisation for units to the max if you will.  the downside is that because of this, large scale battles like 1000 vs 1000, or 10,000 vs 10,000, or in some cases 100,000 vs 100,000 just simply is not possible. the most a person could do without crashing their game too much would most likely be around 400 basic units on the map, with nothing fancy or laggy in the mix. 
with all of this said, it is a great game that will always ensue chaos, cursing, intellectual combat (campaigns), stupidity and so much more! give it a try yourself and you might just taste the fruit of the devil with how hooked you will be!

The Red and Blue factions in TABS are not just random colors chosen for convenience; they are symbolic representations of the notorious Crips and Bloods gangs. The floppy fighters? Mere pawns in the gang warfare chessboard, subtly executing the will of their unseen overlords.

The physics-based battles take on a whole new meaning when you realize they mirror the intricate dance of power and control in the gang-infested streets. Even the comical sound effects take on a sinister undertone, mimicking the echoes of distant sirens and the murmur of hidden conversations.

It's almost as if the developers are inviting players to uncover the deeper layers of TABSCON ‚Äì a conspiracy so well-hidden that only the most astute gamers will discern its true nature.

Despite the shrouded conspiracy, "Totally Accurate Battle Simulator" remains a quirky and entertaining game on the surface. Positive Aspects:

Physics-Based Fun: The game's physics engine is a key highlight. Watching the often absurd and chaotic battles unfold with wobbly, floppy characters can be highly entertaining.

Creative Unit Variety: TABS offers a wide range of units, each with its own quirky abilities and behaviors. Experimenting with different combinations can be both strategic and amusing.

Accessible Gameplay: The game is easy to pick up and play, making it accessible to a broad audience. The simplicity of controls and mechanics allows for casual enjoyment.

Humorous Design: TABS embraces a comedic and lighthearted design. The intentionally goofy animations and unit behaviors contribute to the game's charm.

Regular Updates: The developers have been actively releasing updates, introducing new units, campaigns, and features, which helps keep the game fresh for players.

Negative Aspects:

Limited Single-Player Content: While the single-player campaigns offer some fun scenarios, some players have found the overall single-player content to be somewhat limited. The focus is more on sandbox battles and experimentation.

Graphics and Performance: The intentionally simplistic and goofy graphics might not be appealing to everyone. Additionally, the game may not run optimally on all systems, leading to performance issues for some players.

Lack of Deep Strategy: The game's primary focus is on the chaotic and humorous nature of battles, so it may not satisfy players seeking deep strategic gameplay. The emphasis is more on experimentation and enjoying the unpredictability.

Conclusion:

Totally Accurate Battle Simulator stands out as a whimsical and entertaining experience, particularly for players who enjoy physics-based simulations and quirky, light-hearted gameplay. While it may lack the depth of some strategy games, its charm lies in the sheer unpredictability and amusement derived from watching unconventional battles unfold. The regular updates provided by the developers have contributed to the game's ongoing popularity, making it a good choice for those looking for casual, humorous fun rather than a serious strategy experience.

Positive
-High campaign replayability
-Runs smoothly (unless placing massive quantities of troops, but what else would you expect?)
-Controls are very simple
-Really fun to mess around in sandbox mode

Negative
-Easy to find that a unit may be easy to exploit (such as the scarecrow), potentially leading to a dull time wherein you just use that unit - remember: easily winning isn't the most important thing- get creative!
-No option to turn off only the unit voices, which can get pretty annoying
-Aiming when controlling a unit can be terrible, such as not being able to shoot at a downward angle with the deadeye. However, this may be intentional.
-Sometimes the physics can bug out a bit, whether this be glitching into the ground or a unit holding a weapon around the back of its neck
-Outside of superficial clothing, making custom units offers less customization than you might think

[b]My Opinion:[/b]

TABS is pretty a fun strategy game, where you choose your army and troops and fight people with them, it's a pretty fun game, it just gets a bit boring because you do the same thing over and over, but overall it is a pretty cool game with an awesome concept, there is also many troops for you to choose from, but it gets boring once you have done all of the troops.

I like this game though, some troops do need to be de-buffed though because some are too overpowered.


[b]Downsides:[/b]

There is some troops that can wipe out all of your troops just because they are too strong, it can also be annoying sometimes because some people only end up using one super overpowered troop, over and over.. and it also does get boring because it's the same concept over and over, but I had a fun time overall and enjoyed this game.

TABS Is A game I Hold In High Regards Maybe Not That High But Definitely Higher Than Most Games Ive Played. TABS Put Simply Is A Janky Battle Sim With Way Too Much Charm And Great Design, while Its Not Everyones Cup of Tea Ive been Watching This Game Since Its Beta  Back When Units Were Defined By What Weapon They used And Watched It Slowly Change Into The Great Game It is Today. TABS Game play is Simple At Worst but At Its Core Its A Fun Battle Sim where You Deal with Stupid troops Fighting Against Each Other With Both The Great Testing Unit Known as The Hobbit (halfling) To The Tanky And Large Snuffy (Mammoth) Each And Every unit Has A Distinct Charm And Clear Effort Placed Into It making It Unique.
The In-game Secret Units Are Great case And Point Towards The Cupid Unit To Less Cool Units Such as The ball n Chain But Each One Of These Was "Fun" To Hunt Down And Find But Thats Just Apart of The Game. My Only real Gripes With the game Is That Sometimes Battles Come To Standstills Due To Its Jankyness Such As Units falling through The Fool or Getting A limb Stuck Into The Floor or A Wall. Despite This I Find The Game Great And The Content thats Come From It Funny As hell (Lookin' At You capt. Sauce) So id recommend Applying a Kind of Pokemon Logic To the Game And Looking For Stupid Type Advantages.

To Anyone Looking To Buy This Game Dont take This review At face Value As I Am Definitely A biased Source but Take This Review As A healthy Sign of Love for A Game That Deserves everything Its Gotten over The Years the team At landfall has Done A Great Job And Deserves more Support Behind Their New Endeavors.

A wacky game about assembling AI-controlled armies and pitting them against each other in large scale fights.

[hr][/hr]
Totally Accurate Battle Simulator essentially allows you to set up diverse battles using a massive amount of unity, all boasting mostly unique behaviours, strengths and weaknesses. There are a number of factions these units are split into, ranging from cave men and Vikings to fantasy creatures and modern military among others.

You get to experience using each of these factions during a quite lengthy campaign, which introduces the respective units one after the other, before letting you go wild with the different types of fighters you‚Äôve acquired. Every campaign level sees you go up against a set enemy army, challenging you with experimenting with different strategies to stand victorious. You‚Äôre limited by only having a certain amount of currency, with your different units using up different amounts of it according to their strength. Bought units can be placed freely inside the level levels, giving you some additional strategic opportunities. Said levels also offer quite a bit of variety, with each faction having a set of matching stages which manage to feel quite distinct.

Once you start a battle, all of the units you‚Äôre placed will start moving on their own, automatically attacking the enemy units. While you can simply get a good camera angle to watch the battle unfold, you may also inhabit any of your units, allowing you to move around and use abilities in order to support your troops, which can make a rather big difference. While the campaign starts off rather slow, with mostly trivial levels, the levels quickly become more and more elaborate, with some of the later once requiring a good bit of planning as well as trial and error to complete.

Beyond the campaign, TABS also features a sandbox mode, in which you can freely select any of the included maps and set up armies for either side, essentially without any limits. You may also take part in customizable multiplayer matches in order to test your strategic abilities against human opponents.

A big part of the game‚Äôs charm comes down to its presentation, featuring a low-poly art style with good readability and rather goofy designs, most prominently showcased through the googly eyes all units have. In addition, all attacks as well as the general movement are physics based, leading to units wobbling along and being thrown around by string attacks in rather funny ways. Combined, this makes for quite a fun and rather relaxed experience, with lots to try out for quite a bit of replayability.

Greetings friends, today I want to introduce Totally Accurate Battle Simulator, a funny and entertaining game that ignores the laws of physics. In the game, you can build your own army, place different units as you like and send them into battle and watch the outcome. The game has many different units, from the Stone Age, the Middle Ages, Vikings, ancient Greece and Rome, even pirates and samurai. Each unit has its own characteristics and abilities, some fight with swords, some with arrows, some with spears. Some are much more interesting, like a balloonist, who can tie enemies to balloons and blow them up. Or there's a boxer who knocks enemies down with his fists.

The graphics and sounds of the game are also very nice, especially the sounds the units make. You will have a lot of fun and laugh a lot while playing the game. The controls are simple and easy to use, and I didn't have any difficulties.

It's a bit of a downside that the game is paid, but I think it's worth playing. My least favorite part of the game is that sometimes when there are too many units, the game gets laggy. This disrupts the flow of the game. Also, some parts of the game are very difficult, sometimes I can't pass no matter what I do. But don't give up, maybe you will succeed.

All in all, Totally Accurate Battle Simulator is a perfect game for those who love both history and physics games. The fact that the game is funny and entertaining is another plus. The game has some shortcomings, but it is still worth playing. I liked the game a lot and I recommend it to you too. If you want to play the game, you can buy it on Steam. It's a good game for creation and casual players (Thanks to the custom content), but for those who want to achieve achievements or finish campaigns, it's absolute garbage. This game is really poor in terms of level design and gameplay. There have been some minor updates, but most of the content hasn't changed in years. I wouldn't recommend buying it unless the price is extremely low.

There is a ridiculous difficulty gap between levels in the game due to the horribly unbalanced factions (I suspect the development team didn't think about this at all). Certain levels require little to no mental work and can be completed casually. And some levels, even if you rack your brain, may need to be repeated several times due to bad luck.

A couple of the achievements (finish a campaign without being defeated even once) are almost explicitly asking the player to memorize the countermeasures for each level.

I think these levels are almost completely untested, which makes achieving these achievements even more difficult. I used to play this game in EPIC a few years ago and finished all the campaigns, and now that I'm replaying the game, I still spend quite a long time on certain levels.

Cattle (Bos taurus) are large, domesticated, bovid ungulates. They are prominent modern members of the subfamily Bovinae and the most widespread species of the genus Bos. Mature female cattle are referred to as cows and mature male cattle are referred to as bulls. Colloquially, young female cattle (heifers), young male cattle (bullocks), and castrated male cattle (steers) are also referred to as "cows".

Cattle are commonly raised as livestock for meat (beef or veal, see beef cattle), for milk (see dairy cattle), and for hides, which are used to make leather. They are used as riding animals and draft animals (oxen or bullocks, which pull carts, plows and other implements). Another product of cattle is their dung, which can be used to create manure or fuel. In some regions, such as parts of India, cattle have considerable religious significance. Cattle, mostly small breeds such as the Miniature Zebu, are also kept as pets.

Different types of cattle are common to different geographic areas. Taurine cattle are found primarily in Europe and temperate areas of Asia, the Americas, and Australia. Zebus (also called indicine cattle) are found primarily in India and tropical areas of Asia, America, and Australia. Sanga cattle are found primarily in sub-Saharan Africa. These types (which are sometimes classified as separate species or subspecies) are further divided into over 1,000 recognized breeds.

Don't be fooled by its wobbly art style -- TABS is an incredible, one of a kind masterpiece. Its physics system is on point, and the few times it does break make for hilarious, very much screenshot-able moments. Its strategy, while probably not the most complex or analytical in gaming, is surprisingly deep for a game that only costs $20 at most. The best part is the custom content, allowing for a creator to access every single weapon, ability and unit clothing item in the game, and then some, then combine those all into a quite literally endless variety of different custom units. That means the game's infinite, folks.

TL;DR: Go get yourself a copy of TABS right now. Or else.

Totally Accurate Battle Simulator is quite a unique game, being the extremely goofy strategy war game that it is. I've seen it around while it was still in its development stage. I remember how, though janky, it was very innovative at the time and caused a rise of similar games. Now that I finally got around to playing it, I can see how much it has grown since then.  

The game has a sandbox mode where you can screw around with any of the units in any of the maps and create your own battles, but there are also campaigns where you will need to win a collection of battles against the enemy. Most campaigns will have you face off against a specific faction of units and then give you control of them to fight the other factions. For example, the Renaissance campaign will have you fight against the Renaissance faction, with numerous battles introducing you to each of their units, all having their strengths and weaknesses. You, the red team, will have a limited amount of gold and access to the other factions (you only get the factions that came before the Renaissance update during the game's early access period) that you will need to create your own army to defeat the blue team. At some point in this campaign, the situation is switched where you will have access to the Renaissance faction and the battles will consist of the other factions that you previously had control of.  

I really enjoyed going through these campaigns. Some of these battles are rather frustrating but finding that perfect strategy for each battle can be a very good feeling. The units in TABS have a lot of variety and add loads of interesting combinations for your army composition. Plus, I find them well-designed visually and the sounds they make are great as well, adding personality to them and their factions. This combined with the well-crafted maps gives the game a pretty cool art style. Also, this game‚Äôs physics are absolutely astounding. The units actually manually walk, swing their weapons, and do all sorts of physical activity instead of using pre-made animations . The collisions are phenomenal too as units will touch things on the map as well as each other realistically during battle. Not only does it make the combat feel more organic, but it adds randomness to the combat so that you could play the same battles with the same armies over and over and get a different outcome every time. This kind of complexity in the physics can lead to issues such as one unit holding his weapon behind his back or someone else getting stuck in a tree, but to me that contributes to the hilarity of this game. The intricate physics of the game along with the mechanics of the units made for many cool and funny moments in my playing sessions.  

If you want to play with more kinds of units, factions, maps, battles, or campaigns, then the in-game workshop is where you‚Äôd want to look. The sort of custom content that people managed to create in there is insane. There isn‚Äôt any shortage of overpowered and broken units in the workshop to mess with, so it‚Äôs a good place to check out. Or you could make your own content too. I found the Unit and Map Creators to be relatively easy to use. They contain all the weapons, apparel, abilities, and props that are seen in the base game as well as extra assets that haven‚Äôt been used. I made some units with weapons that aren‚Äôt part of any of the regular units, with some being especially interesting like a bomb bow and a shield that reflected projectiles back at the enemy. If you want even more content to play with, then you could check the mods that are available outside of all that I already mentioned. Some of the mods there look like they could be an official part of the game. 

TABS is certainly one-of-a-kind. Even though it is meant to be a joke game, I can‚Äôt help but appreciate how well-made it is through the gameplay, art style, music, and creative freedom. I didn‚Äôt say about the multiplayer feature as I didn‚Äôt have anyone to play with and trying to find a match didn't work, but other than that, playing this is an absolute blast. It might not be as in-depth as other strategy war games, but it‚Äôs great if you just want to see a bunch of red and blue Play Doh guys clobber each other dead.

Okay, now that's done with, you can do anything in this game its a fun ragdoll where you can control your troops and help defeat the enemy.
